ties are acknowledged and facilitated. In Sweden, they are denied and blocked. Why do these differences exist, and how do both facilitation and hindrance play out in practice?Loneliness and Its Opposite charts complex boundaries between private and public, love and sex, work and intimacy, and affection and abuse. It shows how providing disabled adults with access to sexual lives is not just crucial for a life with dignity. It is an issue of fundamental social justice with far reaching consequences for everyone.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aPeople with disabilitiesxSexual behaviorzDenmark. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxSexual behaviorzSweden. 0aSexxAnthropological aspects. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Sexuality.2bisacsh1 aRydström, Jens, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375845zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375845423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375845.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles